data.name: label27.Text
data.value: When you open an application or folder, it is displayed in its own window. A window is a contained area—like a picture within a picture—with its own menus and buttons specific to that program. You can rearrange multiple windows on the desktop and switch between them.

data.name: label19.Text
data.value: Icons are used to represent the different files, applications, and commands on your computer. An icon is a small image that's intended to give you an idea at a glance of what it represents, like a logo. Double-clicking an icon on the desktop will open that application or file.

data.name: label21.Text
data.value: On laptops, you can use the trackpad, located below the keyboard, instead of a mouse. Simply drag your finger across the trackpad to move the pointer on the screen. Some trackpads do not have buttons, so you'll either press or tap the trackpad to click.

data.name: label20.Text
data.value: The mouse moves the on-screen pointer. Move the mouse, and the pointer moves. Usually, mouses have a left and right button. Interact with the computer by positioning the pointer over an item and clicking a button.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: Once the computer has booted up, it may be ready to use, or it may require you to log in. If prompted to log in, identify yourself by typing your user name or selecting your profile. Then, type your password. If you've never logged in to your computer before, you may need to create an account by following the on-screen instructions.

data.name: label15.Text
data.value: After turning on the computer, you may see a few different displays flash on the screen. This process is called "booting up," and it can take anywhere from 15 seconds to several minutes. Be patient and wait for the computer to complete the booting process.

data.name: label6.Text
data.value: A computer is more than just another household appliance. The vast amount of information and possibilities can be overwhelming. But you can accomplish a lot with a computer, and using one can be a good experience. Let's walk through getting started with your first computer.
